    "shortCode": "DPFW6b3jKkL",
    "caption": "You are who you spend time with. \n\nResearch shows that health-related behaviors ripple through social networks (for better or for worse): \n\n- Drinking habits spread through friend groups.¹\n- When someone quits smoking, their peers are more likely to quit too.²\n- Emotions like happiness (and loneliness) travel up to 3 degrees of separation.³ ⁴\n- Exercise is contagious — friends who move more make you move more.⁵\n\nYour habits don’t just shape your own health — they influence those closest to you, too. \n\nBe the catalyst for positive change. \n\n🧡 P.S. Superpower members, you can now share the health — our referral program is live in your account.\n\nCitations:\n1. Rosenquist, J. N., Murabito, J., Fowler, J. H., & Christakis, N. A. (2010). The spread of alcohol consumption behavior in a large social network. Annals of Internal Medicine, 152(7), 426–433. https://doi.org/10.7326/0003-4819-152-7-201004060-00007\n2. Christakis, N. A., & Fowler, J. H. (2008). The collective dynamics of smoking in a large social network. New England Journal of Medicine, 358(21), 2249–2258. https://doi.org/10.1056/NEJMsa0706154\n3. Fowler, J. H., & Christakis, N. A. (2008). Dynamic spread of happiness in a large social network: Longitudinal analysis over 20 years in the Framingham Heart Study. BMJ, 337, a2338. https://doi.org/10.1136/bmj.a2338\n4. Cacioppo, J. T., Fowler, J. H., & Christakis, N. A. (2009). Alone in the crowd: The structure and spread of loneliness in a large social network. Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 97 (6), 977–991. https://doi.org/10.1037/a0016076\n5. Aral, S., & Nicolaides, C. (2017). Exercise contagion in a global social network. Nature Communications, 8, 14753. https://doi.org/10.1038/ncomms14753",
